[src:curriculum-learning/curriculum-learning] Most generally, curriculum learning is the technique of successively increasing the difficulty of examples in the training set that is presented to a model over multiple training iterations.
[src:curriculum-learning/curriculum-learning] This has been shown to work in many domains, most likely as a form of regularization.
[src:curriculum-learning/curriculum-learning] Since curriculum learning only concerns the selection and ordering of training data, it can be combined with many other techniques in machine learning.
[src:curriculum-learning/curriculum-learning] The success of the method assumes that a model trained for an easier version of the problem can generalize to harder versions, so it can be seen as a form of transfer learning.
[src:curriculum-learning/curriculum-learning] Some authors also consider curriculum learning to include other forms of progressively increasing complexity, such as increasing the number of model parameters.
[src:curriculum-learning/curriculum-learning] It is frequently combined with reinforcement learning, such as learning a simplified version of a game first.
[src:curriculum-learning/curriculum-learning] Some domains have shown success with **anti-curriculum learning**: training on the most difficult examples first.
[src:curriculum-learning/curriculum-learning] One example is the ACCAN method for speech recognition, which trains on the examples with the lowest signal-to-noise ratio first.
[src:curriculum-learning/curriculum-learning] The term "curriculum learning" was introduced by Yoshua Bengio et al in 2009, with reference to the psychological technique of shaping in animals and structured education for humans: beginning with the simplest concepts and then building on them.
[src:curriculum-learning/curriculum-learning] The authors also note that the application of this technique in machine learning has its roots in the early study of neural networks such as Jeffrey Elman's 1993 paper *Learning and development in neural networks: the importance of starting small*.
[src:curriculum-learning/curriculum-learning] Bengio et al showed good results for problems in image classification, such as identifying geometric shapes with progressively more complex forms, and language modeling, such as training with a gradually expanding vocabulary.
[src:curriculum-learning/curriculum-learning] They conclude that, for curriculum strategies, "their beneficial effect is most pronounced on the test set", suggesting good generalization.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The idea is to take repeated steps in the opposite direction of the gradient (or approximate gradient) of the function at the current point, because this is the direction of steepest descent.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Conversely, stepping in the direction of the gradient will lead to a trajectory that maximizes that function; the procedure is then known as *gradient ascent*.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Gradient descent should not be confused with local search algorithms, although both are iterative methods for optimization.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Gradient descent is particularly useful in machine learning and artificial intelligence for minimizing the cost or loss function.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Gradient descent is generally attributed to Augustin-Louis Cauchy, who first suggested it in 1847.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Jacques Hadamard independently proposed a similar method in 1907.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Its convergence properties for non-linear optimization problems were first studied by Haskell Curry in 1944, with the method becoming increasingly well-studied and used in the following decades.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] A simple extension of gradient descent, stochastic gradient descent, serves as the most basic algorithm used for training most deep networks today.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] for a small enough step size or learning rate $\eta \in \mathbb {R} _{+}$ , then $f(\mathbf {a_{n}} )\geq f(\mathbf {a_{n+1}} )$ .
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] In other words, the term $\eta \nabla f(\mathbf {a} )$ is subtracted from $\mathbf {a}$ because we want to move against the gradient, toward the local minimum.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] so the sequence $(\mathbf {x} _{n})$ converges to the desired local minimum.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Note that the value of the *step size* $\eta$ is allowed to change at every iteration.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] It is possible to guarantee the convergence to a local minimum under certain assumptions on the function f (for example, f convex and $\nabla f$ Lipschitz) and particular choices of $\eta$ .
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] as in the Barzilai-Borwein method, or a sequence $\eta _{n}$ satisfying the Wolfe conditions (which can be found by using line search).
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] When the function f is convex, all local minima are also global minima, so in this case gradient descent can converge to the global solution.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] This process is illustrated in the adjacent picture.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Here, f is assumed to be defined on the plane, and that its graph has a bowl shape.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The blue curves are the contour lines, that is, the regions on which the value of f is constant.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] A red arrow originating at a point shows the direction of the negative gradient at that point.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Note that the (negative) gradient at a point is orthogonal to the contour line going through that point.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] We see that gradient *descent* leads us to the bottom of the bowl, that is, to the point where the value of the function f is minimal.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The basic intuition behind gradient descent can be illustrated by a hypothetical scenario.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] People are stuck in the mountains and are trying to get down (i.e., trying to find the global minimum).
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] There is heavy fog such that visibility is extremely low.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Therefore, the path down the mountain is not visible, so they must use local information to find the minimum.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] They can use the method of gradient descent, which involves looking at the steepness of the hill at their current position, then proceeding in the direction with the steepest descent (i.e., downhill).
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] If they were trying to find the top of the mountain (i.e., the maximum), then they would proceed in the direction of steepest ascent (i.e., uphill).
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Using this method, they would eventually find their way down the mountain or possibly get stuck in some hole (i.e., local minimum or saddle point), like a mountain lake.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] However, assume also that the steepness of the hill is not immediately obvious with simple observation, but rather it requires a sophisticated instrument to measure, which the people happen to have at that moment.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] It takes quite some time to measure the steepness of the hill with the instrument.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Thus, they should minimize their use of the instrument if they want to get down the mountain before sunset.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The difficulty then is choosing the frequency at which they should measure the steepness of the hill so as not to go off track.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] In this analogy, the people represent the algorithm, and the path taken down the mountain represents the sequence of parameter settings that the algorithm will explore.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The steepness of the hill represents the slope of the function at that point.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The instrument used to measure steepness is differentiation.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The direction they choose to travel in aligns with the gradient of the function at that point.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The amount of time they travel before taking another measurement is the step size.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Since using a step size $\eta$ that is too small would slow convergence, and a $\eta$ too large would lead to overshoot and divergence, finding a good setting of $\eta$ is an important practical problem.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Philip Wolfe also advocated using "clever choices of the [descent] direction" in practice.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] While using a direction that deviates from the steepest descent direction may seem counter-intuitive, the idea is that the smaller slope may be compensated for by being sustained over a much longer distance.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Finding good settings of $\mathbf {p} _{n}$ and $\eta _{n}$ requires some thought.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] First of all, we would like the update direction to point downhill.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Mathematically, letting $\theta _{n}$ denote the angle between $-\nabla f(\mathbf {a_{n}} )$ and $\mathbf {p} _{n}$ , this requires that $\cos \theta _{n}>0.$ To say more, we need more information about the objective function that we are optimising.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] This inequality implies that the amount by which we can be sure the function f is decreased depends on a trade off between the two terms in square brackets.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The first term in square brackets measures the angle between the descent direction and the negative gradient.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The second term measures how quickly the gradient changes along the descent direction.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] In principle inequality (**1**) could be optimized over $\mathbf {p} _{n}$ and $\eta _{n}$ to choose an optimal step size and direction.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The problem is that evaluating the second term in square brackets requires evaluating $\nabla f(\mathbf {a} _{n}-t\eta _{n}\mathbf {p} _{n})$ , and extra gradient evaluations are generally expensive and undesirable.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Usually by following one of the recipes above, convergence to a local minimum can be guaranteed.
