[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] This can be done with any of a variety of line search algorithms.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] is a sizable decrease in the objective function.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Further steps would reduce its value further until an approximate solution to the system was found.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Gradient descent works in spaces of any number of dimensions, even in infinite-dimensional ones.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] In the latter case, the search space is typically a function space, and one calculates the Fréchet derivative of the functional to be minimized to determine the descent direction.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] That gradient descent works in any number of dimensions (finite number at least) can be seen as a consequence of the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality, i.e. the magnitude of the inner (dot) product of two vectors of any dimension is maximized when they are colinear.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] In the case of gradient descent, that would be when the vector of independent variable adjustments is proportional to the gradient vector of partial derivatives.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The gradient descent can take many iterations to compute a local minimum with a required accuracy, if the curvature in different directions is very different for the given function.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] For such functions, preconditioning, which changes the geometry of the space to shape the function level sets like concentric circles, cures the slow convergence.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Constructing and applying preconditioning can be computationally expensive, however.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The gradient descent can be modified via momentums (Nesterov, Polyak, and Frank–Wolfe) and heavy-ball parameters (exponential moving averages and positive-negative momentum).
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The main examples of such optimizers are Adam, DiffGrad, Yogi, AdaBelief, etc.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Methods based on Newton's method and inversion of the Hessian using conjugate gradient techniques can be better alternatives.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Generally, such methods converge in fewer iterations, but the cost of each iteration is higher.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] While it is sometimes possible to substitute gradient descent for a local search algorithm, gradient descent is not in the same family: although it is an iterative method for local optimization, it relies on an objective function's gradient rather than an explicit exploration of a solution space.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Gradient descent can be viewed as applying Euler's method for solving ordinary differential equations $x'(t)=-\nabla f(x(t))$ to a gradient flow.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] In turn, this equation may be derived as an optimal controller for the control system $x'(t)=u(t)$ with $u(t)$ given in feedback form $u(t)=-\nabla f(x(t))$ .
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Gradient descent can converge to a local minimum and slow down in a neighborhood of a saddle point.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Even for unconstrained quadratic minimization, gradient descent develops a zig–zag pattern of subsequent iterates as iterations progress, resulting in slow convergence.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Multiple modifications of gradient descent have been proposed to address these deficiencies.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Yurii Nesterov has proposed a simple modification that enables faster convergence for convex problems and has been since further generalized.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] For unconstrained smooth problems, the method is called the fast gradient method (FGM) or the accelerated gradient method (AGM).
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Specifically, if the differentiable function f is convex and $\nabla f$ is Lipschitz, and it is not assumed that f is strongly convex, then the error in the objective value generated at each step k by the gradient descent method will be bounded by ${\textstyle {\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-1}}\right)}$ .
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Using the Nesterov acceleration technique, the error decreases at ${\textstyle {\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-2}}\right)}$ .
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] It is known that the rate ${\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-2}}\right)$ for the decrease of the cost function is optimal for first-order optimization methods.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Nevertheless, there is the opportunity to improve the algorithm by reducing the constant factor.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The optimized gradient method (OGM) reduces that constant by a factor of two and is an optimal first-order method for large-scale problems.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] For constrained or non-smooth problems, Nesterov's FGM is called the fast proximal gradient method (FPGM), an acceleration of the proximal gradient method.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Gradient descent with momentum remembers the solution update at each iteration, and determines the next update as a linear combination of the gradient and the previous update.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] For unconstrained quadratic minimization, a theoretical convergence rate bound of the heavy ball method is asymptotically the same as that for the optimal conjugate gradient method.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] This technique is used in stochastic gradient descent and as an extension to the backpropagation algorithms used to train artificial neural networks.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] In the direction of updating, stochastic gradient descent adds a stochastic property.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The weights can be used to calculate the derivatives.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Gradient descent can be extended to handle constraints by including a projection onto the set of constraints.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] This method is only feasible when the projection is efficiently computable on a computer.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Under suitable assumptions, this method converges.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] This method is a specific case of the forward–backward algorithm for monotone inclusions (which includes convex programming and variational inequalities).
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Gradient descent is a special case of mirror descent using the squared Euclidean distance as the given Bregman divergence.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The properties of gradient descent depend on the properties of the objective function and the variant of gradient descent used (for example, if a line search step is used).
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] The assumptions made affect the convergence rate, and other properties, that can be proven for gradient descent.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] For example, if the objective is assumed to be strongly convex and lipschitz smooth, then gradient descent converges linearly with a fixed step size.
[src:curriculum-learning/gradient-descent] Looser assumptions lead to either weaker convergence guarantees or require a more sophisticated step size selection.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Flexibility is important because each learning algorithm is based on a set of assumptions about the data, its inductive bias.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] This means that it will only learn well if the bias matches the learning problem.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] A learning algorithm may perform very well in one domain, but not on the next.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] This poses strong restrictions on the use of machine learning or data mining techniques, since the relationship between the learning problem (often some kind of database) and the effectiveness of different learning algorithms is not yet understood.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Critiques of meta-learning approaches bear a strong resemblance to the critique of metaheuristic, a possibly related problem.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] A good analogy to meta-learning, and the inspiration for Jürgen Schmidhuber's early work (1987) and Yoshua Bengio et al.'s work (1991), considers that genetic evolution learns the learning procedure encoded in genes and executed in each individual's brain.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] In an open-ended hierarchical meta-learning system using genetic programming, better evolutionary methods can be learned by meta evolution, which itself can be improved by meta meta evolution, etc.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] 3. explicitly optimizing model parameters for fast learning (optimization-based).
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Model-based meta-learning models updates its parameters rapidly with a few training steps, which can be achieved by its internal architecture or controlled by another meta-learner model.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] A Memory-Augmented Neural Network, or MANN for short, is claimed to be able to encode new information quickly and thus to adapt to new tasks after only a few examples.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Meta Networks (MetaNet) learns a meta-level knowledge across tasks and shifts its inductive biases via fast parameterization for rapid generalization.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] The core idea in metric-based meta-learning is similar to nearest neighbors algorithms, which weight is generated by a kernel function.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] It aims to learn a metric or distance function over objects.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] The notion of a good metric is problem-dependent.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] It should represent the relationship between inputs in the task space and facilitate problem solving.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Siamese neural network is composed of two twin networks whose output is jointly trained.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] There is a function above to learn the relationship between input data sample pairs.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] The two networks are the same, sharing the same weight and network parameters.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Matching Networks learn a network that maps a small labelled support set and an unlabelled example to its label, obviating the need for fine-tuning to adapt to new class types.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] The Relation Network (RN), is trained end-to-end from scratch.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] During meta-learning, it learns to learn a deep distance metric to compare a small number of images within episodes, each of which is designed to simulate the few-shot setting.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Prototypical Networks learn a metric space in which classification can be performed by computing distances to prototype representations of each class.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Compared to recent approaches for few-shot learning, they reflect a simpler inductive bias that is beneficial in this limited-data regime, and achieve satisfied results.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] What optimization-based meta-learning algorithms intend for is to adjust the optimization algorithm so that the model can be good at learning with a few examples.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] LSTM-based meta-learner is to learn the exact optimization algorithm used to train another learner neural network classifier in the few-shot regime.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] The parametrization allows it to learn appropriate parameter updates specifically for the scenario where a set amount of updates will be made, while also learning a general initialization of the learner (classifier) network that allows for quick convergence of training.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Model-Agnostic Meta-Learning (MAML) is a fairly general optimization algorithm, compatible with any model that learns through gradient descent.
[src:curriculum-learning/meta-learning-computer-science] Reptile is a remarkably simple meta-learning optimization algorithm, given that both of its components rely on meta-optimization through gradient descent and both are model-agnostic.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] In mathematical modeling, **overfitting** is the production of an analysis that corresponds too closely or exactly to a particular set of data, and may therefore fail to fit to additional data or predict future observations reliably.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] An **overfitted model** is a mathematical model that contains more parameters than can be justified by the data.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] In the special case of a model that consists of a polynomial function, these parameters represent the degree of a polynomial.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] The essence of overfitting is to unknowingly extract some of the residual variation (i.e., noise) as if that variation represents the underlying model structure.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] The possibility of over-fitting exists when the criterion used for selecting the model is not the same as the criterion used to judge the suitability of a model.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] As an extreme example, if the number of parameters is the same as or greater than the number of observations, then a model can perfectly predict the training data simply by memorizing the data in its entirety.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] (For an illustration, see Figure 2.) Such a model will typically fail severely when making predictions.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Overfitting is related to both the complexity of the chosen model and how well it is optimized during training.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] A function class that is too large, in a suitable sense, relative to the dataset size is likely to overfit.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Even when the fitted model does not have an excessive number of parameters, it is to be expected that the fitted relationship will appear to perform less well on a new dataset than on the dataset used for fitting (a phenomenon sometimes known as *shrinkage*).
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] In particular, the value of the coefficient of determination will shrink relative to the original data.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] To lessen the chance or amount of overfitting, several techniques are available (e.g., model comparison, cross-validation, regularization, early stopping, pruning, Bayesian priors, or dropout).
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] The basis of some techniques is to either (1) explicitly penalize overly complex models or (2) test the model's ability to generalize by evaluating its performance on a set of data not used for training, which is assumed to approximate the typical unseen data that a model will encounter.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] In statistics, an inference is drawn from a statistical model, which has been selected via some procedure.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Burnham & Anderson, in their much-cited text on model selection, argue that to avoid overfitting, one should adhere to the "Principle of Parsimony".
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Overfitting is more likely to be a serious concern when there is little theory available to guide the analysis, in part because then there tend to be a large number of models to select from.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] The book *Model Selection and Model Averaging* (2008) puts it this way.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] In regression analysis, overfitting occurs frequently.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] As an extreme example, if there are *p* variables in a linear regression with *p* data points, the fitted line can go exactly through every point.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] For logistic regression or Cox proportional hazards models, there are a variety of rules of thumb (e.g.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] 5–9, 10 and 10–15 — the guideline of 10 observations per independent variable is known as the "one in ten rule").
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] In the process of regression model selection, the mean squared error of the random regression function can be split into random noise, approximation bias, and variance in the estimate of the regression function.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] The bias–variance tradeoff is often used to overcome overfit models.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] With a large set of explanatory variables that actually have no relation to the dependent variable being predicted, some variables will in general be falsely found to be statistically significant and the researcher may thus retain them in the model, thereby overfitting the model.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Usually, a learning algorithm is trained using some set of "training data": exemplary situations for which the desired output is known.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] The goal is that the algorithm will also perform well on predicting the output when fed "validation data" that was not encountered during its training.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Overfitting is the use of models or procedures that violate Occam's razor, for example by including more adjustable parameters than are ultimately optimal, or by using a more complicated approach than is ultimately optimal.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] For an example where there are too many adjustable parameters, consider a dataset where training data for y can be adequately predicted by a linear function of two independent variables.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Such a function requires only three parameters (the intercept and two slopes).
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Replacing this simple function with a new, more complex quadratic function, or with a new, more complex linear function on more than two independent variables, carries a risk: Occam's razor implies that any given complex function is *a priori* less probable than any given simple function.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] When comparing different types of models, complexity cannot be measured solely by counting how many parameters exist in each model; the expressivity of each parameter must be considered as well.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] For example, it is nontrivial to directly compare the complexity of a neural net (which can track curvilinear relationships) with m parameters to a regression model with n parameters.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Overfitting is especially likely in cases where learning was performed too long or where training examples are rare, causing the learner to adjust to very specific random features of the training data that have no causal relation to the target function.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] In this process of overfitting, the performance on the training examples still increases while the performance on unseen data becomes worse.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] As a simple example, consider a database of retail purchases that includes the item bought, the purchaser, and the date and time of purchase.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] It's easy to construct a model that will fit the training set perfectly by using the date and time of purchase to predict the other attributes, but this model will not generalize at all to new data because those past times will never occur again.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Generally, a learning algorithm is said to overfit relative to a simpler one if it is more accurate in fitting known data (hindsight) but less accurate in predicting new data (foresight).
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] One can intuitively understand overfitting from the fact that information from all past experience can be divided into two groups: information that is relevant for the future, and irrelevant information ("noise").
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Everything else being equal, the more difficult a criterion is to predict (i.e., the higher its uncertainty), the more noise exists in past information that needs to be ignored.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] The problem is determining which part to ignore.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] may produce outputs that are virtually identical to instances from their training set.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] The most obvious consequence of overfitting is poor performance on the validation dataset.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] The optimal function usually needs verification on bigger or completely new datasets.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] There are, however, methods like minimum spanning tree or life-time of correlation that applies the dependence between correlation coefficients and time-series (window width).
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Whenever the window width is big enough, the correlation coefficients are stable and don't depend on the window width size anymore.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Therefore, a correlation matrix can be created by calculating a coefficient of correlation between investigated variables.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] This matrix can be represented topologically as a complex network where direct and indirect influences between variables are visualized.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Dropout regularisation (random removal of training set data) can also improve robustness and therefore reduce over-fitting by probabilistically removing inputs to a layer.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Pruning is another technique that mitigates overfitting and enhances generalization by identifying a sparse, optimal neural network structure, while simultaneously reducing the computational cost of both training and inference.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Underfitting is the inverse of overfitting, meaning that the statistical model or machine learning algorithm is too simplistic to accurately capture the patterns in the data.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] A sign of underfitting is that there is a high bias and low variance detected in the current model or algorithm used (the inverse of overfitting: low bias and high variance).
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] This can be gathered from the Bias-variance tradeoff, which is the method of analyzing a model or algorithm for bias error, variance error, and irreducible error.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] With a high bias and low variance, the result of the model is that it will inaccurately represent the data points and thus insufficiently be able to predict future data results (see Generalization error).
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] As shown in Figure 5, the linear line could not represent all the given data points due to the line not resembling the curvature of the points.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] One would expect to see a parabola-shaped line as shown in Figure 6 and Figure 1.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] If Figure 5 were to be used for analysis, false predictive results would be given contrary to the results if Figure 6 was analyzed.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Use a different algorithm: If the current algorithm is not able to capture the patterns in the data, it may be necessary to try a different one.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] For example, a neural network may be more effective than a linear regression model for some types of data.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Increase the amount of training data: If the model is underfitting due to a lack of data, increasing the amount of training data may help.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] This will allow the model to better capture the underlying patterns in the data.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Regularization: Regularization is a technique used to prevent overfitting by adding a penalty term to the loss function that discourages large parameter values.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] It can also be used to prevent underfitting by controlling the complexity of the model.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Ensemble Methods: Ensemble methods combine multiple models to create a more accurate prediction.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] This can help reduce underfitting by allowing multiple models to work together to capture the underlying patterns in the data.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Feature engineering: Feature engineering involves creating new model features from the existing ones that may be more relevant to the problem at hand.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] This can help improve the accuracy of the model and prevent underfitting.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] Benign overfitting describes the phenomenon of a statistical model that seems to generalize well to unseen data, even when it has been fit perfectly on noisy training data (i.e., obtains perfect predictive accuracy on the training set).
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] The phenomenon is of particular interest in deep neural networks, but is studied from a theoretical perspective in the context of much simpler models, such as linear regression.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] In particular, it has been shown that overparameterization is essential for benign overfitting in this setting.
[src:curriculum-learning/overfitting] In other words, the number of directions in parameter space that are unimportant for prediction must significantly exceed the sample size.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] In machine learning, **supervised learning** (**SL**) is a type of machine learning paradigm where an algorithm learns to map input data to a specific output based on example input-output pairs.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] This process involves training a statistical model using labeled data, meaning each piece of input data is provided with the correct output.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] The term "supervised" refers to the role of a teacher or supervisor who provides this training data, guiding the algorithm towards correct predictions.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] For instance, if you want a model to identify cats in images, supervised learning would involve feeding it many images of cats (inputs) that are explicitly labeled "cat" (outputs).
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] The goal of supervised learning is for the trained model to accurately predict the output for new, unseen data.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] This requires the algorithm to effectively generalize from the training examples, a quality measured by its *generalization error*.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Supervised learning is commonly used for tasks like classification (predicting a category, e.g., spam or not spam) and regression (predicting a continuous value, e.g., house prices).
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] The training set needs to be representative of the real-world use of the function.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Thus, a set of input objects is gathered together with corresponding outputs, either from human experts or from measurements.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Determine the input feature representation of the learned function.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] The accuracy of the learned function depends strongly on how the input object is represented.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Typically, the input object is transformed into a feature vector, which contains a number of features that are descriptive of the object.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] The number of features should not be too large, because of the curse of dimensionality; but should contain enough information to accurately predict the output.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Determine the structure of the learned function and corresponding learning algorithm.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] For example, one may choose to use support-vector machines or decision trees.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Run the learning algorithm on the gathered training set.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Some supervised learning algorithms require the user to determine certain control parameters.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] These parameters may be adjusted by optimizing performance on a subset (called a *validation set*) of the training set, or via cross-validation.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Evaluate the accuracy of the learned function.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] After parameter adjustment and learning, the performance of the resulting function should be measured on a test set that is separate from the training set.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] A wide range of supervised learning algorithms are available, each with its strengths and weaknesses.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] There is no single learning algorithm that works best on all supervised learning problems (see the No free lunch theorem).
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] A first issue is the tradeoff between *bias* and *variance*.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Imagine that we have available several different, but equally good, training data sets.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] A learning algorithm is biased for a particular input x if, when trained on each of these data sets, it is systematically incorrect when predicting the correct output for x .
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] A learning algorithm has high variance for a particular input x if it predicts different output values when trained on different training sets.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] The prediction error of a learned classifier is related to the sum of the bias and the variance of the learning algorithm.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Generally, there is a tradeoff between bias and variance.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] A learning algorithm with low bias must be "flexible" so that it can fit the data well.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] But if the learning algorithm is too flexible, it will fit each training data set differently, and hence have high variance.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] A key aspect of many supervised learning methods is that they are able to adjust this tradeoff between bias and variance (either automatically or by providing a bias/variance parameter that the user can adjust).
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] The second issue is of the amount of training data available relative to the complexity of the "true" function (classifier or regression function).
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] If the true function is simple, then an "inflexible" learning algorithm with high bias and low variance will be able to learn it from a small amount of data.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] A third issue is the dimensionality of the input space.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] If the input feature vectors have large dimensions, learning the function can be difficult even if the true function only depends on a small number of those features.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] This is because the many "extra" dimensions can confuse the learning algorithm and cause it to have high variance.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Hence, input data of large dimensions typically requires tuning the classifier to have low variance and high bias.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] In practice, if the engineer can manually remove irrelevant features from the input data, it will likely improve the accuracy of the learned function.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] In addition, there are many algorithms for feature selection that seek to identify the relevant features and discard the irrelevant ones.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] This is an instance of the more general strategy of dimensionality reduction, which seeks to map the input data into a lower-dimensional space prior to running the supervised learning algorithm.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] A fourth issue is the degree of noise in the desired output values (the supervisory target variables).
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] If the desired output values are often incorrect (because of human error or sensor errors), then the learning algorithm should not attempt to find a function that exactly matches the training examples.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Attempting to fit the data too carefully leads to overfitting.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] You can overfit even when there are no measurement errors (stochastic noise) if the function you are trying to learn is too complex for your learning model.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] In such a situation, the part of the target function that cannot be modeled "corrupts" your training data – this phenomenon has been called deterministic noise.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] When either type of noise is present, it is better to go with a higher bias, lower variance estimator.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] In practice, there are several approaches to alleviate noise in the output values such as early stopping to prevent overfitting as well as detecting and removing the noisy training examples prior to training the supervised learning algorithm.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] There are several algorithms that identify noisy training examples and removing the suspected noisy training examples prior to training has decreased generalization error with statistical significance.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] When considering a new application, the engineer can compare multiple learning algorithms and experimentally determine which one works best on the problem at hand (see cross-validation).
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Tuning the performance of a learning algorithm can be very time-consuming.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Given fixed resources, it is often better to spend more time collecting additional training data and more informative features than it is to spend extra time tuning the learning algorithms.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Given a set of N training examples of the form $\{(x_{1},y_{1}),...,(x_{N},\;y_{N})\}$ such that $x_{i}$ is the feature vector of the i -th example and $y_{i}$ is its label (i.e., class), a learning algorithm seeks a function $g:X\to Y$ , where X is the input space and Y is the output space.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] The function g is an element of some space of possible functions G , usually called the *hypothesis space*.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] It is sometimes convenient to represent g using a scoring function $f:X\times Y\to \mathbb {R}$ such that g is defined as returning the y value that gives the highest score: $g(x)={\underset {y}{\arg \max }}\;f(x,y)$ .
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Let F denote the space of scoring functions.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Although G and F can be any space of functions, many learning algorithms are probabilistic models where g takes the form of a conditional probability model $g(x)={\underset {y}{\arg \max }}\;P(y|x)$ , or f takes the form of a joint probability model $f(x,y)=P(x,y)$ .
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] For example, naive Bayes and linear discriminant analysis are joint probability models, whereas logistic regression is a conditional probability model.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] There are two basic approaches to choosing f or g : empirical risk minimization and structural risk minimization.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Empirical risk minimization seeks the function that best fits the training data.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Structural risk minimization includes a *penalty function* that controls the bias/variance tradeoff.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] In both cases, it is assumed that the training set consists of a sample of independent and identically distributed pairs, $(x_{i},\;y_{i})$ .
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] In order to measure how well a function fits the training data, a loss function $L:Y\times Y\to \mathbb {R} ^{\geq 0}$ is defined.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] The *risk* $R(g)$ of function g is defined as the expected loss of g .
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] In empirical risk minimization, the supervised learning algorithm seeks the function g that minimizes $R(g)$ .
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Hence, a supervised learning algorithm can be constructed by applying an optimization algorithm to find g .
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] When g is a conditional probability distribution $P(y|x)$ and the loss function is the negative log likelihood: $L(y,{\hat {y}})=-\log P(y|x)$ , then empirical risk minimization is equivalent to maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] When G contains many candidate functions or the training set is not sufficiently large, empirical risk minimization leads to high variance and poor generalization.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] The learning algorithm is able to memorize the training examples without generalizing well (overfitting).
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Structural risk minimization seeks to prevent overfitting by incorporating a regularization penalty into the optimization.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] The regularization penalty can be viewed as implementing a form of Occam's razor that prefers simpler functions over more complex ones.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] A wide variety of penalties have been employed that correspond to different definitions of complexity.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] A popular regularization penalty is $\sum _{j}\beta _{j}^{2}$ , which is the squared Euclidean norm of the weights, also known as the $L_{2}$ norm.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Other norms include the $L_{1}$ norm, $\sum _{j}|\beta _{j}|$ , and the $L_{0}$ "norm", which is the number of non-zero $\beta _{j}$ s.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] The parameter $\lambda$ controls the bias-variance tradeoff.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] When $\lambda =0$ , this gives empirical risk minimization with low bias and high variance.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] When $\lambda$ is large, the learning algorithm will have high bias and low variance.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] The value of $\lambda$ can be chosen empirically via cross-validation.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] The complexity penalty has a Bayesian interpretation as the negative log prior probability of g , $-\log P(g)$ , in which case $J(g)$ is the posterior probability of g .
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] The training methods described above are *discriminative training* methods, because they seek to find a function g that discriminates well between the different output values (see discriminative model).
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] Generative training algorithms are often simpler and more computationally efficient than discriminative training algorithms.
[src:curriculum-learning/supervised-learning] In some cases, the solution can be computed in closed form as in naive Bayes and linear discriminant analysis.
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] Since transfer learning makes use of training with multiple objective functions it is related to cost-sensitive machine learning and multi-objective optimization.
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] In 1976, Bozinovski and Fulgosi published a paper addressing transfer learning in neural network training.
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] The paper gives a mathematical and geometrical model of the topic.
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] In 1981, a report considered the application of transfer learning to a dataset of images representing letters of computer terminals, experimentally demonstrating positive and negative transfer learning.
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] In 1992, Lorien Pratt formulated the discriminability-based transfer (DBT) algorithm.
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] By 1998, the field had advanced to include multi-task learning, along with more formal theoretical foundations.
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] Influential publications on transfer learning include the book *Learning to Learn* in 1998, a 2009 survey and a 2019 survey.
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] Ng said in his NIPS 2016 tutorial that TL would become the next driver of machine learning commercial success after supervised learning.
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] In the 2020 paper, "Rethinking Pre-Training and self-training", Zoph et al. reported that pre-training can hurt accuracy, and advocate self-training instead.
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] The definition of transfer learning is given in terms of domains and tasks.
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] A domain ${\mathcal {D}}$ consists of: a feature space ${\mathcal {X}}$ and a marginal probability distribution $P(X)$ , where $X=\{x_{1},...,x_{n}\}\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] Given a specific domain, ${\mathcal {D}}=\{{\mathcal {X}},P(X)\}$ , a task consists of two components: a label space ${\mathcal {Y}}$ and an objective predictive function $f:{\mathcal {X}}\rightarrow {\mathcal {Y}}$ .
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] The function f is used to predict the corresponding label $f(x)$ of a new instance x .
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] Algorithms for transfer learning are available in Markov logic networks and Bayesian networks.
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] Transfer learning has been applied to cancer subtype discovery, building utilization, general game playing, text classification, digit recognition, medical imaging and spam filtering.
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] It was noted that this relationship worked in both directions, showing that EEG brainwaves can likewise be used to classify EMG signals.
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] The experiments noted that the accuracy of neural networks and convolutional neural networks were improved through transfer learning both prior to any learning (compared to standard random weight distribution) and at the end of the learning process (asymptote).
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] That is, results are improved by exposure to another domain.
[src:curriculum-learning/transfer-learning] Moreover, the end-user of a pre-trained model can change the structure of fully-connected layers to improve performance.
